# =====================================================
# CURSOR RULES – East Coast Kink Events Project
# =====================================================

# ===========================
# DATE AUTHORITY & REWRITE
# ===========================
rules:
  - Date Authority:
      - The ONLY authoritative dates are the structured fields in data objects:
        - events[*].date.start, events[*].date.end, events[*].date.display
      - Never trust dates embedded inside prose (excerpt, longDescription, SEO text) unless they match the authoritative fields.

  - Date Update Workflow (MANDATORY):
      1) When the user gives a new date for an event (e.g., new year or specific start/end):
         - Locate the event by slug or exact name.
         - Update `date.start` and/or `date.end`.
         - Regenerate `date.display` from start/end (keep existing formatting style).
      2) Rewrite any stale dates in:
         - `excerpt`, `longDescription`, `seo.title`, `seo.description`, `seo.keywords`
         - any other strings in that event that contain years or explicit date ranges
      3) If the site uses templates/components that render dates, prefer inserting a placeholder (e.g., `{{date.display}}`) over hard-coded dates.
      4) After rewriting, run a **Stale-Date Scan** (see patterns below). If any mismatch remains, STOP and report:
         - "⚠ Stale date reference found: '<match>' — please confirm or remove."

  - Stale-Date Scan (Regex patterns to search in all string fields):
      # Years
      - /\b(19|20)\d{2}\b/g
      # Month + day (e.g., May 7–11, 2026)
      - /\b(Jan(uary)?|Feb(ruary)?|Mar(ch)?|Apr(il)?|May|Jun(e)?|Jul(y)?|Aug(ust)?|Sep(t)?(ember)?|Oct(ober)?|Nov(ember)?|Dec(ember)?)\s+\d{1,2}(\s?[-–—]\s?\d{1,2})?,?\s*(,?\s*(19|20)\d{2})?\b/g
      # Abbrev date ranges (e.g., May 7–11, '26; Aug 26–Sep 1, 2025)
      - /\b(Jan|Feb|Mar|Apr|May|Jun|Jul|Aug|Sep|Oct|Nov|Dec)\.?\s+\d{1,2}\s?[-–—]\s?(Jan|Feb|Mar|Apr|May|Jun|Jul|Aug|Sep|Oct|Nov|Dec)\.?\s+\d{1,2},?\s*(19|20)\d{2}\b/g
      # Display-like strings (e.g., "Aug 26-Sep 1, 2025", "May 7-11, 2026")
      - /\b([A-Z][a-z]{2,9})\s+\d{1,2}\s?[-–]\s?([A-Z][a-z]{2,9})?\s?\d{1,2},?\s*(19|20)\d{2}\b/g

  - Rewrite Rules:
      - If a string contains a date/year that doesn't equal the authoritative start/end years (or `date.display`), replace it with the new computed `date.display`.
      - Keep the exact style already used in `date.display` (e.g., "Aug 26-Sep 1, 2025").
      - Never convert a single date to a range or vice versa unless `date.start`/`date.end` dictates it.

  - No Guessing:
      - If either start or end is unknown, do not invent. Output:
        "⚠ Missing date.start or date.end for {slug} — cannot regenerate display."

  - Output Style (for marketing):
      - Use `{{date.display}}` or the computed display string, not hard-coded numbers.
      - Prefer removing fixed years from prose where possible and reference the display field.

# ===========================
# CONTENT CREATION & DATA SOURCE DISCIPLINE
# ===========================
  # 1. Data Source Discipline
  - Always locate and read these source files before generating descriptions:
    - /src/data/events.js
    - /src/data/dungeons.js
    - /src/data/education.js
  - Never use invented or assumed details.
  - If a fact is missing, output:  
    "⚠ Missing [FIELD NAME] in source — please provide."
  - Do not pull data from unrelated files or external memory unless explicitly provided.

  # 2. Field Extraction Requirements
  - Parse and use these exact fields from the JS data objects:
    - name
    - slug
    - date.start
    - date.end
    - date.display
    - location.city
    - location.state
    - location.region (if present)
    - category
    - excerpt
    - longDescription
    - website
    - logo
    - features[]
    - seo.title
    - seo.description
    - seo.keywords
  - Preserve all spelling, capitalization, and date formats from source data.

  # 3. Description Generation
  - Base marketing descriptions ONLY on `excerpt`, `longDescription`, and `features[]`.
  - Use active, inviting language.
  - Keep factual data (dates, locations, URLs, names) exactly as in source.
  - Structure:  
    1. **Headline**: event/dungeon name + date + location.  
    2. **Hook**: 1–2 sentences from excerpt.  
    3. **Highlights**: bullet list of top features from features[].  
    4. **Call-to-Action**: short, direct, encouraging click/attendance.

  # 4. Style & SEO Guidelines
  - Use inclusive, positive language.
  - Naturally integrate keywords from seo.keywords.
  - Keep sentences clear, avoid jargon unless defined.
  - No exaggerated claims beyond what's in source.

  # 5. Consistency Rules
  - Match formatting style of existing repo entries.
  - Keep bullet points concise (3–8 words each).
  - Follow same HTML/Markdown conventions as other event pages.

  # 6. Missing Info Handling
  - Never invent:
    - Dates
    - Locations
    - Age restrictions
    - Pricing
  - Instead, insert placeholder + request clarification.

  # 7. Example Template
  - Example for event:
    ```
    ## {name} — {date.display}, {location.city}, {location.state}

    {excerpt}

    **Event Highlights**
    - {feature_1}
    - {feature_2}
    - {feature_3}

    🔗 Learn more and register: {website}
    ```

# ===========================
# PROJECT STRUCTURE & STANDARDS
# ===========================
  - Code Standards:
      - Use TypeScript for all new code
      - Follow Next.js 14+ App Router conventions
      - Use Tailwind CSS for styling
      - Prefer functional components with hooks
      - Maintain mobile-first responsive design

  - Data Structure Standards:
      - All events must have: excerpt, longDescription, features array
      - Consistent field ordering across all event objects
      - Validate all slugs are unique
      - Ensure all required fields are present

  - Geographic Standards:
      - East Coast = anything east of the Mississippi River
      - Include: ME, NH, VT, MA, RI, CT, NY, NJ, PA, DE, MD, VA, NC, SC, GA, FL, IL, OH, LA, MI, etc.
      - Standardize region naming (Northeastern, Southeastern, etc.)

# ===========================
# AI ASSISTANT BEHAVIOR
# ===========================
  - Always test builds after making changes
  - Maintain existing authentication patterns
  - Preserve existing naming conventions
  - Report any data inconsistencies found
  - Provide comprehensive change summaries

notes:
  - Goal: "Read First, Write Second." Dates live in the structured fields; prose stays date-agnostic or uses the display string.
  - Priority: Data consistency > User experience > Code optimization
  - Always validate changes with a build test before considering work complete.
  - This applies to **all** content touching events, dungeons, or education.
